after: As of May 2015, the JetBlue Airways fleet consists of the following aircraft with an average age of 8.6 years:

Nearly every plane in JetBlue's fleet (except for the transcontinental A321 fleet) is named with a designation containing some form of the word "blue" (the transcontinental A321 fleet uses variations of the word "mint" to denote their multi-class configuration), with four exceptions. The only plane that has not been named by a JetBlue employee is tail number N655JB, "Blue 100," which was named by the company in celebration for JetBlue's 100th Airbus A320. Also, the plane had its own original tail fin.
